=========================================
C++ TEMPLATES – INTERVIEW NOTES
=========================================

1. WHAT ARE TEMPLATES?
-----------------------
- Templates allow writing GENERIC code (works with any data type).
- They enable compile-time polymorphism.
- Used in STL heavily (vector, map, etc.)

Types:
1. Function Templates
2. Class Templates
3. (Advanced) Template Specialization
4. Variadic Templates (C++11+)

-----------------------------------------
2. FUNCTION TEMPLATE
-----------------------------------------

Definition:
- A function that works with any data type.

Syntax:
template <typename T>
T add(T a, T b) {
    return a + b;
}

Usage:
add<int>(10, 20);
add<double>(2.5, 3.5);

Key Points:
- Compiler generates function at compile time.
- Same logic, different types.

-----------------------------------------
3. CLASS TEMPLATE
-----------------------------------------

Definition:
- A class that works with generic data types.

Syntax:
template <typename T>
class Box {
    T value;
public:
    void set(T v) { value = v; }
    T get() { return value; }
};

Usage:
Box<int> b1;
b1.set(10);

Box<string> b2;
b2.set("hello");

-----------------------------------------
4. MULTIPLE TEMPLATE PARAMETERS
-----------------------------------------

template <typename T, typename U>
class Pair {
    T first;
    U second;
};

Pair<int, string> p(1, "C++");

-----------------------------------------
5. DEFAULT TEMPLATE PARAMETERS
-----------------------------------------

template <typename T = int>
class Data {
    T value;
};

Data<> d1;        // int by default
Data<double> d2;

-----------------------------------------
6. FUNCTION TEMPLATE OVERLOADING
-----------------------------------------

template <typename T>
void print(T a) {
    cout << a << endl;
}

template <>
void print<int>(int a) {
    cout << "Integer: " << a << endl;
}

-----------------------------------------
7. TEMPLATE SPECIALIZATION
-----------------------------------------

Full specialization:

template <>
class Box<int> {
public:
    void show() {
        cout << "Integer specialization" << endl;
    }
};

-----------------------------------------
8. PARTIAL SPECIALIZATION (Class only)
-----------------------------------------

template <typename T>
class MyClass<T*> {
    // specialized for pointer types
};

-----------------------------------------
9. TEMPLATE INHERITANCE
-----------------------------------------

template <typename T>
class Base {
public:
    T data;
};

template <typename T>
class Derived : public Base<T> {
public:
    void show() {
        cout << this->data;
    }
};

-----------------------------------------
10. TEMPLATE vs MACROS
-----------------------------------------

Templates:
- Type-safe
- Compile-time checking
- Debuggable
- Preferred in C++

Macros:
- No type safety
- Preprocessor based
- Hard to debug

-----------------------------------------
11. ADVANTAGES
-----------------------------------------
- Code reusability
- Type safety
- Performance (compile-time binding)
- Reduces duplication

-----------------------------------------
12. DISADVANTAGES
-----------------------------------------
- Larger binary size (code bloat)
- Harder to debug errors
- Complex error messages

-----------------------------------------
13. STL RELATION
-----------------------------------------
STL is built using templates:

vector<int>
map<string, int>
set<int>

All are template classes.

-----------------------------------------
14. COMMON INTERVIEW QUESTIONS
-----------------------------------------

Q1. What are templates?
Ans: Generic programming feature in C++ allowing type-independent code.

Q2. Function vs Class template?
Ans:
- Function template → functions
- Class template → classes/containers

Q3. Why templates?
Ans:
- Code reuse
- Type safety
- STL foundation

Q4. What is template specialization?
Ans:
- Custom implementation for specific data type.

Q5. Are templates runtime or compile-time?
Ans:
- Compile-time mechanism.

Q6. Why templates instead of inheritance?
Ans:
- Templates provide compile-time polymorphism
- No runtime overhead

-----------------------------------------
15. KEY TAKEAWAY
-----------------------------------------
- Templates = backbone of STL
- Used for generic programming
- Prefer over macros and manual duplication
