=========================================
C++ TEMPLATES – MOST ASKED Q&A
=========================================

1. What is a template in C++?
--------------------------------
Ans:
A template is a feature in C++ that allows writing generic code
so that the same function/class works with different data types.
It is resolved at compile time.

-----------------------------------------

2. Why do we need templates?
--------------------------------
Ans:
- To avoid code duplication
- To achieve type safety
- To support generic programming
- Used heavily in STL (vector, map, etc.)

-----------------------------------------

3. Difference between function template and class template?
--------------------------------
Ans:

Function Template:
- Works for functions
- Example: add<T>(T a, T b)

Class Template:
- Works for classes/objects
- Example: vector<T>, map<K,V>

-----------------------------------------

4. Are templates runtime or compile-time?
--------------------------------
Ans:
Templates are COMPILE-TIME mechanisms.
Compiler generates code for each type used.

-----------------------------------------

5. What is template specialization?
--------------------------------
Ans:
Providing a specific implementation of a template
for a particular data type.

Example:
template <>
class Box<int> {
    // custom implementation for int
};

-----------------------------------------

6. What is function template overloading?
--------------------------------
Ans:
You can overload function templates or specialize them
for specific types.

Example:
template <typename T>
void print(T a);

template <>
void print<int>(int a);

-----------------------------------------

7. What is partial specialization?
--------------------------------
Ans:
Specializing a template for a subset of types.

NOTE:
- Allowed only for class templates
- Not allowed for function templates

Example:
template <typename T>
class MyClass<T*> {  // pointer specialization
};

-----------------------------------------

8. Can templates be inherited?
--------------------------------
Ans:
Yes. Template classes can inherit from other templates.

Example:
template <typename T>
class Base {};

template <typename T>
class Derived : public Base<T> {};

-----------------------------------------

9. What is template instantiation?
--------------------------------
Ans:
When compiler generates actual code for a given type.

Example:
vector<int> → compiler creates vector<int> class.

-----------------------------------------

10. What is code bloat in templates?
--------------------------------
Ans:
Templates generate separate code for each type,
which can increase binary size.

-----------------------------------------

11. Why are templates better than macros?
--------------------------------
Ans:
Templates:
- Type-safe
- Debuggable
- Compile-time checking

Macros:
- No type safety
- Preprocessor based
- Hard to debug

-----------------------------------------

12. What is default template parameter?
--------------------------------
Ans:
You can assign default type to template.

Example:
template <typename T = int>
class Data {};

Data<> d;  // int used by default

-----------------------------------------

13. Can templates be overloaded?
--------------------------------
Ans:
Yes, function templates can be overloaded.
But class template overloading is not typical;
instead specialization is used.

-----------------------------------------

14. What is STL relation with templates?
--------------------------------
Ans:
STL is fully built using templates:
- vector<T>
- map<K,V>
- set<T>

All are template classes.

-----------------------------------------

15. What is variadic template?
--------------------------------
Ans:
Template that accepts variable number of arguments.

Example:
template <typename... Args>
void func(Args... args);

Used in modern C++ (C++11+).

-----------------------------------------

16. What happens if template code has error?
--------------------------------
Ans:
Errors appear during instantiation,
often producing long and complex compiler messages.

-----------------------------------------

17. Can we use templates for non-type parameters?
--------------------------------
Ans:
Yes.

Example:
template <int N>
class Array {
    int arr[N];
};

-----------------------------------------

18. Are templates polymorphism?
--------------------------------
Ans:
Yes → compile-time polymorphism (static binding),
unlike virtual functions (runtime polymorphism).

-----------------------------------------

19. Can we separate template declaration and definition?
--------------------------------
Ans:
Usually NO (must be in header file)
because compiler needs full definition during instantiation.

-----------------------------------------

20. Key Interview Summary
--------------------------------
- Templates = generic programming
- Compile-time mechanism
- Backbone of STL
- Replace repetitive code
=========================================


